projectInfo.description:
- Author: **Missing Maps**
- Requesting organization: **Netherlands Red Cross**
- Priority: **Medium**

Through this mapping task the Netherlands Red Cross supports the Malawi Red Cross Society to:


 * enhance** resilience** and building institutional disaster response capacity training for the people of Malawi

 * **raise awareness** within vulnerable communities in disaster prone areas of the possible dangers of natural disasters. 

 * improve the delivery of **sustainable water supply, sanitation and hygiene** services in these low-income areas 

 * respond to a **food crisis** to meet drought affected population’s food and nutrition needs through cash transfer.

Mapping efforts are coordinated with local government / members of the HOT/OSM community in Malawi.

The Missing Maps project aims to map the most vulnerable places in the world (affected by humanitarian crises: disease epidemics, conflict, natural disasters, poverty, environmental crises). Building on HOT's disaster preparedness projects, the Missing Maps tasks facilitate pre-emptive mapping of priority countries to better facilitate disaster response, medical activities and resource allocation when crises occur.
projectInfo.instructions:
Please click on a square to start mapping. If there are many objects to map, you can split the task in 4 smaller tiles. Make sure you read below how to adjust the imagery offset before starting to map! Also read the task instructions on how to map roads and buildings.

Imageries
========
Please **use the BING imagery for the location & if necessary compare with DigitalGlobe  Imagery**. 

Task
========
Buildings. Simply trace the outline of all buildings. A building should be tagged as a Building of type Building (because we don't know the exact function of that building from satellite imagery). Make sure you SQUARE (shortcut key = 'S' in iD editor) the corners of square/rectangular buildings.

Trace any missing roads:
The only primary road in this region (M1) is is outside this proejct. 

**Secondary roads**: important roads, branching of the M1 connecting district with each other. There are only a very few of these roads in this area. Most of them are on the map, but some pieces are missing yet,.

**Tertiary roads**: a road, usually unpaved, connecting villages with other. 

**Residential roads**: road in a town or village, with a row of buildings on one or both sides of the road.

**Minor unclassified**: roads to isolated villages and houses. You can drive a car on these roads

**Path**: small road, where you cannot drive a car, too narrow or too winding

As a general rule, don't trace roads that don't lead to any building. It is easy to mistake small rivers and borders of aggricultural areas for roads.

Cloud cover
========
If you cannot finish the tile due to cloud coverage, you can successfully complete the tasks, then save your changes, mention 'cloud coverage' in the comment when you save the task, and mark the task as done.

Validation
========
We kindly request advanced mappers and validators to contribute to validating the work of others. Be aware of the **right alignment** of the DigitalGlobe images to BING. This is not the same over the area, so check this everytime you start a validating a tile.

* Map missing roads, buildings, and main waterways.

 * Correct buildings. Some buildings are not properly drawn. See if you can correct them to match the shape of the building on the satellite imagery. If a building is not squared but should be, apply squaring to the buildings (this is most easily done in JOSM where all buildings can be selected and squared with one click.

 * Correct roads. Some roads will be misaligned or just misinterpreted.

If you finish validating a tile. Save your changes, mark it as validated in the HOT tasking manager, and leave a comment to the original contributors i.e.: 'thank you for mapping all these buildings and roads. We made a few corrections. Please consider squaring the buildings in your future work, and make sure that you don't miss any'


Further tagging resources
========
See [Highway Africa Tag page](http://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Highway_Tag_Africa) for further advice on tagging roads and [the OSM map features page](http://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Map_Features) for more info.
